PLN 105 million for companies from the video game industry from the National Centre for Research and Development
Almost PLN 105 million of co-financing will go to companies from the gaming industry, creating innovative solutions.
The National Centre for Research and Development announced the results of the third edition of the GameINN program on Friday.
Among the nearly 30 projects supported by the NCBR, included the development of a platform for creating field games based on the AR game engine creating a real world map with an application enabling data transmission by users; a test and training platform to verify practical skills in the workplace and professional development using VR and AI technology; an innovative game simulating the management of real production processes using an innovative model of gameplay based on the interaction of the virtual industry with the application of the global concept.
The aim of the GameINN sectoral programme is to increase the competitiveness of the Polish sector of video game producers on the global market by 2023.
According to the NCBR, the Polish video game sector is already growing at a rate of 10% per year.
According to government data, the value of the Polish video game market in 2016 amounted to PLN 1.85 billion, and the forecast for 2019 is 2.23 billion.
“The specialist research agenda of GameINN and the already PLN 300 million support for entrepreneurs under this sectoral program are an important impulse for the further, dynamic growth of Polish gamedevu,” the statement said.
The video game industry is a perfect example of effective use of the potential we have in Poland.
“Incentemers introduced by the government for innovation-involving entrepreneurs, such as R&D reliefs, competence improvement programs, IP box or support programs implemented by the NCBR drive the innovative activities of companies and allow them to compete more effectively on a very competitive market,” says Deputy Prime Minister, Minister of Science and Higher Education Jarosław Gowin, quoted in the release.
The head of the Ministry of Science points out that money for innovations not only goes to innovators in the form of co-financing projects, but also stays in their pockets – three-quarters of more entrepreneurs benefited from the R&D relief in 2018 than a year earlier.
“The amount of deducted costs related to R&D activities amounted to PLN 1.7 billion, which resulted in over PLN 300 million of savings for companies benefiting from this relief.
This is the equivalent of the support provided by the NCBR in three editions of GameINN”, emphasizes the Deputy Prime Minister.
Director of the NCBR Dr. inż. Wojciech Kamieniecki reminds that in the two previous competitions, 78 innovative projects were awarded to PLN 211.2 million.
The huge interest in the third competition and the variety of submitted applications show that the video game industry has ideas and competences to further develop and increase its competitive advantages.
“It is particularly pleasing that among the selected projects – as in previous editions – there are projects on solutions for not only entertainment, but also related to industry 4.0,” he adds.
In the third GameINN competition for co-financing of up to PLN 20 million, entrepreneurs, consortia of entrepreneurs and consortia of entrepreneurs with scientific units could apply for co-financing of up to PLN 20 million.
The NCBR received 87 applications for the total amount of co-financing of approx. 317 million zlotys.
The budget of the competition at the time of the announcement of the competition was PLN 100 million, but it was increased, thanks to which 27 projects were granted almost PLN 105 million of co-financing.
Detailed information about the results of the 3rd GameINN competition can be found on the ncbr.gov.pl website.
The GameINN sectoral programme is implemented under the Smart Growth Operational Programme.
NCBR launched the program in 2016 in response to the initiative of entrepreneurs associated in the Polskie Gry Agreement, which includes companies such as CD Projekt, Techland, CI Games, Bloober Team or 11 bit studios.
