According to the specialist, the main threat to the Polish economy is the downturn in the world.
“The global slowdown may still be worse, but there should be no severe recession, and at most the rise of GDP growth slightly below zero,” Bolliger said.
“Investors should be underweighted by global actions that may be undermined by the lack of prospects for resolving the U.S.-China trade conflict and other geopolitical risk factors, including Donald Trump’s impeachment procedure and Brexit.
Europe should be relatively weaker among the stock markets,” according to the latest letter to investors by UBS Wealth Management Mark Haefele.
