“42 percent of the tree species that make up the tree stand of Europe are at risk,” warns the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) in the “Red Book of European Trees” published on Friday.
At the top of the list are, among others, chestnut trees and rowan.
IUCN, an organisation based in Gland, Switzerland, publishes a list of endangered European tree species for the first time.
It was drawn up by specialists who, on the basis of the research, concluded that of the 454 tree species found in Europe (as well as elsewhere in the world), 42% are “highly threatened”.
Among the reasons, the Red Paper lists the rapid growth of urban agglomerations and global climate change.
However, the most endangered are those trees and shrubs that occur only or mainly on our continent.
As for the typical European stands, according to IUCN specialists, 58% of species are at risk and 15 percent, i.e. 66 species of trees and shrubs, threaten to die.
Among the main reasons for deforestation, the Red Book lists errors in the operation of the stand, accelerated urbanization, excessively intense felling of trees, and then forest fires and changes taking place in the European eco-stimism.
According to the authors of the report, the existence of many European varieties of shrubs, mosses and lichens is also very much in danger.
“The consequences of human activities lead to the gradual disappearance of European plant species and pose in Europe the danger of extinction of important and underestimated varieties that underpin European ecosystems and have an impact on the health of our planet,” concluded the report by Luc Bas, which heads the European IUCN office.
