"Rzeczpospolita": Ignoring the order of the policeman will be punished
According to the newspaper, disregarding the order of certain behavior issued by a police officer is to be a new type of offence, punishable by a fine, arrest or restriction of freedom.
The introduction of such a change is wanted by the police trade unionists.
The idea went to the Sejm’s Committee on Petitions.
“The issue is serious, because already every year more than half a million offences go to Polish courts,” we read.
“Rzeczpospolita” has determined that the petition, which the Independent Trade Union of Police is writing to MPs on changing the code of offences has a chance to succeed.
The petitioners propose a new wording of the article. 54a of the Code of Offences.
He would read: “Anyone who does not submit to the request or command of a public official, issued within the limits and under the provisions of the Act, shall be subject to a penalty of arrest, a fine or restriction of freedom.”
“The couple. 3 of this provision refers to the same penalty for those who, without following instructions, will prevent or hinder the performance of a work," the log says.
Sociologist Andrzej Kowalski said that although he agrees with the main message of the proposal of the provision, he fears that if implemented, it can be used in matters of political manifestations.
“In situations of libertarian demonstrations, it would be unfavorable and instead of alleviating the situation, even to exacerbate it,” he adds.
Statistics reported by the newspaper show that 86 percent of citizens positively assessed police interventions in 2018 and that the services take 1.5 million interventions in the city each month.
