Brussels Airlines cancels 105 flights due to Thomas Cook bankruptcy
Although the British travel agency Thomas Cook has collapsed, his Belgian subsidiary Neckermann is in operation.
The company has problems.
Brussels Airlines has announced that it will cancel 105 flights in October due to problems related to the bankruptcy of Thomas Cook.
Neckermann also laid off 75 employees.
All trips with the office that have been booked in Belgium will be cancelled, but holidaymakers will be able to receive a refund.
The Gandawa court also declared the bankruptcy of three Belgian daughter companies: Thomas Cook Belgium, Thomas Cook Retail and Thomas Cook Financial Services.
Now it's OK. 12,000. Belgians are abroad on trips purchased from Thomas Cook.
Another 40,000 people were to leave with the office by the end of the year.
As recently as Monday, spokeswoman Thomas Cook Belgium Leen Segers said the company was now “fully operational” despite the UK’s mother’s bankruptcy, which caused anxiety among employees and customers.
The office reassured that customers who bought trips in it would go on vacation.
Thomas Cook, the oldest and one of the largest travel agencies in the world, declared bankruptcy on the night of Sunday to Monday.
The direct cause of bankruptcy was the collapse of last resort talks with creditors and potential investors on Sunday.
The creditors demanded that in addition to the 900 million-pound rescue plan already agreed in August, the company would get an additional 200 million as collateral for the winter period when travel agencies usually have lower turnover.
However, the company’s problems have been growing for several years, resulting in a debt of 1.6 billion pounds.
