Goerlitz in Germany offers free accommodation for your opinion
Free accommodation in exchange for an opinion – such an extraordinary offer was prepared for the newcomer by the German Goerlitz.
Actions are intended to help in the fight against the progressive decline in the number of inhabitants of the city.
Goerlitz is Germany’s easternmost city.
The beautiful pastel old town attracts 140,000 tourists a year.
However, according to The Guardian, the city is facing significant problems.
There are the lowest wages in Germany.
The city is also struggling with a steady decline in the number of inhabitants.
After the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, most of them went to the west of the country, which translated into a 25% decrease in the city’s population.
In 2013, it was 54,000.
Wanting to fight the depopulation, officials came up with the idea to start offering free monthly accommodation in the city.
For now, 150 applications have been received by the programme.
Two-thirds of them were made by residents of large cities.
People from Hungary, the Czech Republic, the United States and the United Kingdom were also interested in the program.
“When we were applying, we thought the program was supposed to convince people to move to Goerlitz,” said one of the project participants.
“Now we feel that it doesn’t matter if we’re staying here after four weeks or not,” he added.
The city has 7,000 vacancies, and unemployment is three times higher than the average nationwide.
Although the city authorities hope that some will move permanently, the main goal of the program is to obtain the opinions of the participants of the program.
The information gathered from interviews and questionnaires is intended to help revive smaller German cities.
“We want to learn more about what people need, and if they decide to move – what their motivation was,” said Robert Knippschild, in charge of the program.
Other cities have already experimented with ideas to luring new residents, offering them incentives in the form of accommodation.
The first was Detroit, which introduced a program to pay promising young professionals for living and working in the city for a year.
Today, such solutions are used in many places, from the Greek island of Antikythera to Candela in Italy, or in the American Tulsa, Oklahoma.
